<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The Maryland male from Cabin John (Spencer and Steyskal 1986) and the North Carolina male examined and illustrated here, were both identified as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rondani" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Cerodontha" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cerodontha" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Cerodontha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
&quot;near angulata&quot; by Spencer, and tentatively assigned to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Malloch" baseAuthorityYear="1916" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Cerodontha" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cerodontha subangulata" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subangulata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Cerodontha subangulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Compared to the holotype, the tubules of the distiphallus of these males are more slender and shallowly curved. Since the length of crossvein dm-m is shorter than the length of this vein from r-m, as seen in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. angulata" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="angulata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. angulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, this character is no longer considered diagnostically valuable. The collection of additional material is essential to properly establishing species boundaries and morphological variation, which will hopefully supply additional characters to use in the identification key.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
